## 3 Overly Saturated but Well-Generalized Model

The phenomenon of saturation refers to the state in which a neuron predominantly outputs values close to the asymptotic ends of the bounded activation function . When training a neural network with bounded activation functions, the outputs of neurons increase due to the gradually increasing weights . The increased output values become close to the near asymptote in bounded activation functions, as shown in the experiment in Glorot & Bengio . However, excessive saturation damages the neural network, and it is regarded as a situation to evade [4; 15; 16; 1; 2; 11]. Various methods were proposed to prevent excessive saturation. Glorot & Bengio  proposed an initialization scheme, Rakitianskaia & Engelbrecht [15; 16] proposed a metric to measure the degree of saturation for monitoring the training, Bhat et al.  pre-scaled the inputs of the activation function, and Chen & Chang  proposed adaptable bounded activation.

